        "title": "Indian mangoes have been banned from Japan",
        "title_zh": "印度芒果被日本拒之门外",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-07-11/24",
        "summary_md": "### 🌟 一句话核心主旨\n日本以印度鲜芒果未能通过病虫害检疫为由实施进口禁令,这一最新事件折射出印度从田间到港口全链条的系统性食品安全危机。\n\n### 🔍 核心观点与论据拆解\n- 日本禁令的最新引爆点:印度作为全球最大芒果生产国,其鲜芒果因病虫害检疫不合格遭日本禁运;同时印度的香料、海产品和大米在美国、欧洲及亚洲均面临限制、禁运或额外检查,欧盟在过去两年内对印度各类食品发出了 365 次警报。\n- 源头问题在农场:印度农药滥用与禁用化学品使用司空见惯,合格的病虫害防控却难以普及;腐败与监管松懈使农药残留、药物残留及沙门氏菌等微生物顺畅地沿供应链上行,直抵海外市场。\n- 经济损失巨大且信誉受创:一个香料货柜价值就超过 10 万美元,被检验机构拒收直接造成损失;欧盟已对印度辣椒和咖喱叶 20%–50% 的货物实施实验室检测,费用由生产商自行承担,长期信誉损害更难量化。\n- 印度本国消费者是最大受害者:印度食品安全标准局(FSSAI)2024–25 年度抽检中近五分之一样品不合格;古吉拉特邦一次突击检查查获准备用于榨汁的虫蛀和发霉芒果;非法化学催熟可致器官衰竭,长期摄入特定农药则增加患癌风险。\n- 孟加拉国经验可借鉴:过去十年孟加拉国基本消除了用于给姜黄增色的铬酸铅中毒问题,该添加剂可致脑部和心脏疾病,并严重损害儿童认知发育;其做法包括总理层级公开介入、震撼性电视宣传、张贴 5 万份市场通告并将姜黄掺假入罪;印度虽早已将其列为犯罪,却执行不力,文章认为印度应向这一常被轻视的邻国学习。\n\n### 🤨 争议与潜在挑战\n原文未涉及明显争议。\n\n### 🔮 未来趋势预判\n若印度不能在全国层面建立从农场到港口的出口追溯体系并增设供应链检测实验室,类似日本芒果禁令的出口受阻事件将持续发生,甚至扩展到更多品类;与此同时,国内食品安全乱象也将进一步侵蚀消费者健康与「印度制造」的海外品牌信誉。",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">Asia</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | Forbidden fruit</span></p>\n<h1>Indian mangoes have been banned from Japan</h1>\n<h3>It’s the latest sign of a widespread food-safety problem</h3>\n<h3>July 9th 2026</h3>\n<p>Hundreds of people had gathered to honour India’s favourite fruit. Braving the heat in Delhi’s Lodhi Gardens, a rapper riffed on the double meaning of aam, the Hindi word for both mango and common, as in common man. People dressed in mango-themed outfits were lectured by a mango farmer. Finally, the party, the fifth to be organised by an enthusiast named Ravinder Singh, descended into the mass munching of 120kg of the stuff.</p>\n<p>Japan won’t be having any, though. It has banned fresh mango imports from India, after the world’s biggest producer failed its pest-control checks. India flunks a lot of such tests. Its spices, seafood and rice all face restrictions, bans and extra inspections in America, Europe and Asia. The EU has issued 365 alerts against various Indian food products in the past two years. The problem begins on farms, where runaway pesticide use and banned chemicals are common and good pest control is not. Corruption and lax monitoring mean that pesticides, drug residues and microbial bugs like salmonella then travel smoothly up the supply chain.</p>\n<p>Bad food is bad for business. A single cargo container of spices can be worth over $100,000, so rejection by inspectors hurts. Harder to measure are reputational hits and extra inspection costs in the future. The EU already lab-tests 20-50% of all Indian chilli and curry-leaf shipments—at the producers’ expense.</p>\n<p>The biggest victims are unsuspecting Indians. Almost one in five samples that the Food Safety and Standards Authority of India tested in 2024-25 failed. One recent raid in Gujarat unearthed a stockpile of worm-eaten and fungus-infected mangoes destined for juice. Artificial ripening—a banned but common chemical trick—can cause organ failure. Other things can kill over decades: the bigger the amount of certain pesticides you consume, the greater the risk of cancer. </p>\n<p>Some fixes are for policy wonks. There could be a national farm-to-port tracing system for agricultural exports, and more testing labs along the supply chain. Other solutions may require high-level input. Over the past decade  Bangladesh has virtually eliminated poisoning from lead chromate, a chemical that was frequently added to the spice turmeric to enhance its colour. Lead is toxic to humans, increasing the risk of brain and heart disease, and particularly dangerous to children because it can stunt their cognitive development.</p>\n<p>Bangladesh’s action against the additive involved public intervention from the prime minister, as well as a graphic TV campaign and the plastering of 50,000 notices in markets and other public areas. Adulteration of turmeric with the chemical was made a crime; India had done that earlier, but failed to implement its rules. It could do a lot worse than learn from its often looked-down-upon neighbour. <span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>Stay on top of our India coverage by <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/newsletters/essential-india\">signing up to Essential India</a>, our free weekly newsletter.</p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//asia/2026/07/09/indian-mangoes-have-been-banned-from-japan\">https://www.economist.com//asia/2026/07/09/indian-mangoes-have-been-banned-from-japan</a> </p>"
