        "id": "art_2026-07-11_025",
        "section": "Asia",
        "category": "analysis",
        "title": "How South Korean Buddhists are trying to stay relevant",
        "title_zh": "韩国佛教如何努力保持时代相关性",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-07-11/25",
        "summary_md": "### 🌟 一句话核心主旨\n面对年轻人宗教热情普遍消退的困境,韩国佛教界通过机器人僧侣、潮牌周边、冥想节和相亲会等现代化、年轻化手段吸引Z世代,以求在世俗化浪潮中维持生存与影响力。\n\n### 🔍 核心观点与论据拆解\n1. **机器人僧侣与潮酷周边引爆关注**:2026年5月,名为「Gabi」的人形机器人僧侣在大邱韩国佛教文化博览会上亮相,26岁的Bae Ji-yun等参观者身着印有「Shut up and meditate」等口号的文化衫;首尔类似博览会吸引25万名游客,且以年轻人为主。\n2. **Z世代在经济压力中转向佛教寻求慰藉**:韩国年轻人生活压力与竞争加剧,2004年以来经济上不活跃的青年人数几乎增至三倍;25岁的Kim Su-jin等信众认为佛教的「苦」哲学能提供内在平静,而非依赖神祇。\n3. **佛教受世俗好评但信徒持续流失**:民调显示佛教仍是世俗韩国人评价最高的宗教,《Life Hacks from the Buddha》等正念书籍跻身畅销榜,去年寺庙接待过夜客人数量创历史新高;然而韩国最大宗派曹溪宗(Jogye order)的新增剃度人数已降至二十年前的三分之一以下。\n4. **佛教领袖筹谋生存之策**:去年韩国佛教宗团协会(Association of Buddhist Orders in Korea)召开会议,聚焦在保持佛教「不强迫」传统优势的同时,激发信众持久参与,为此举办舞蹈派对、冥想节乃至单身相亲活动。\n5. **传统与现代的张力并存**:始建于五世纪的直指寺(Jikjisa Temple)的Seo One法师认为佛教历来拥抱「超越阶级与年龄」的非正统文化;但韩国佛教文化团(Cultural Corps of Korean Buddhism)的Il Hwa法师警告核心教义恐在被「挑选消费」中流失;潮牌Haetal Company创始人Ju Yeo-jin则表示佛教对她而言「一直非常有趣且很酷」。\n\n### 🤨 争议与潜在挑战\n文章呈现两派分歧:改革派以Seo One法师为代表,认为舞蹈派对、相亲会等营销手段是佛教一贯「超越阶级与年龄」传统的延续;保守派以Il Hwa法师为代表,担忧佛教核心教义在年轻人「挑挑拣拣」的浅层接触中被遗忘,长期将削弱宗教根基。\n\n### 🔮 未来趋势预判\n若潮流化策略持续奏效,韩国佛教或将凭借机器人、AI技术与潮牌联名维持年轻群体的曝光度;然而如何把「Shut up and meditate」式的浅层消费转化为持久信仰、扭转曹溪宗剃度人数持续下滑的局面,仍是佛教界亟需破解的长期命题。",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">Asia</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | The middle way to Gen Z</span></p>\n<h1>How South Korean Buddhists are trying to stay relevant</h1>\n<h3>Life is suffering; the Buddha can help</h3>\n<h3>July 9th 2026</h3>\n<p>A ROBOT MONK trundles across the exhibition hall of the Korean Buddhism Culture Expo in the city of Daegu. The humanoid, called Gabi, was unveiled in May and has since generated a new buzz about an ancient religion. Buddhists in South Korea have recently been trying to appear less old-fashioned, says Bae Ji-yun, a 26-year-old attending the expo and sifting through T-shirts bearing slogans such as “Shut up and meditate”. Their efforts seem to be paying off. The event used to draw mainly Buddhists, but it increasingly attracts casual shoppers too. A similar expo this year in Seoul, the capital, drew a quarter of a million visitors, mostly youngsters. </p>\n<p>Gloomy young Koreans are drawn to Buddhism. Young adults report that life is increasingly stressful and competitive. The number of young who are economically inactive is said to have nearly tripled since 2004. Buddhism, which views suffering as an unavoidable feature of life and strives to rise above it, offers them some comfort. The religion generates faith in oneself rather than in a deity, says Kim Su-jin, a 25-year-old who recently trekked to a temple in search of inner peace. Buddhism remains the religion viewed most favourably by secular Koreans, a recent poll shows. Books about mindfulness such as “Life Hacks from the Buddha” are bestsellers. Last year temples hosted a record number of overnight guests.</p>\n<p>Buddhist leaders hope the interest will revitalise their fading religion. South Koreans, especially young ones, are becoming less religious overall. The number of practising Buddhists is shrinking. Fewer new monks join monasteries: ordinations within the Jogye order, the largest in South Korea, have dropped to less than a third of their level two decades ago.</p>\n<p>Last year, the Association of Buddhist Orders in Korea convened to discuss Buddhism’s survival in the country. The latest challenge is to arouse lasting engagement while remaining uncoercive—one of Buddhism’s key selling points. </p>\n<p>To appeal to younger people, Buddhist orders are these days throwing dance parties and meditation festivals. Some temples even host matchmaking events for singles. These aren’t gimmicks, says the Venerable Seo One of the Jikjisa Temple, one of the Koreas’ oldest, dating back to the fifth century. Buddhism, she says, has always embraced “an unorthodox culture that transcends class and age”. Others fear the religion is being cherry-picked. “The core beliefs may get lost,” worries the Venerable Il Hwa of the Cultural Corps of Korean Buddhism.</p>\n<p>It may be so. Hipster brands sell merch and preach the importance of inner wellbeing. One brand, Haetal Company, prints Buddhism-inspired memes on mugs and plastic key-chains. “I have always found Buddhism incredibly fun and cool,” says Ju Yeo-jin, its founder. The knick-knacks may not be a path to true enlightenment, but at least they are lifting spirits. <span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>For exclusive coverage of Asian politics, economics and security, sign up to <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/newsletters/asia-bulletin\">Asia Bulletin</a>, our weekly subscriber-only newsletter.</p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//asia/2026/07/09/how-south-korean-buddhists-are-trying-to-stay-relevant\">https://www.economist.com//asia/2026/07/09/how-south-korean-buddhists-are-trying-to-stay-relevant</a> </p>"
