        "section": "Britain",
        "category": "analysis",
        "title": "Some Scottish wrens are a striking case of “island syndrome”",
        "title_zh": "苏格兰部分鹪鹩呈现显著的『岛屿综合征』",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-07-11/46",
        "summary_md": "### 🌟 一句话核心主旨\n苏格兰圣基尔达群岛和设得兰群岛上的鹪鹩亚种因长期与英国大陆隔绝，独立演化出显著的『岛屿综合征』，体型远超大陆同类，是岛屿巨型化最极端的案例之一。\n\n### 🔍 核心观点与论据拆解\n1. 岛屿综合征理论：孤岛物种因脱离大陆捕食者、面临较少的资源竞争，常出现『小动物变大、大动物变小』的演化趋势，如毛里求斯渡渡鸟从鸽子大小演化为火鸡大小并丧失飞行能力。\n2. 研究发现：发表于《林奈学会进化期刊》的论文指出，圣基尔达与设得兰两个群岛上的鹪鹩亚种与大陆隔绝数千年后，体型已显著大于英国本土鹪鹩。\n3. 研究方法：第一作者米哈尔·耶杰尔斯基带领团队以雾网配合鹪鹩鸣声录音进行诱捕，尽管鹪鹩极具领地意识、仅回唱拒绝出网，最终仍成功捕获45只个体用于系统研究。\n4. 数据对比：结合苏格兰国家博物馆的历史标本与英国鸟类学信托基金会的体重记录，并与另外695对岛屿-大陆鸟类对比，结果显示费尔岛鹪鹩体型与大陆相近，外赫布里底群岛略大，圣基尔达与设得兰鹪鹩最为巨大，最重者达最小大陆鹪鹩的两倍。\n5. 极端程度与平行演化：这两个巨型亚种跻身已知岛屿巨型化案例最极端的前25%，可与全球最重的鹦鹉——新西兰鸮鹦鹉相提并论；尽管体型相似，二者控制体型的基因重叠极少，表明它们通过不同遗传路径平行演化。\n\n### 🤨 争议与潜在挑战\n原文未涉及明显争议。\n\n### 🔮 未来趋势预判\n圣基尔达与设得兰鹪鹩以不同基因路径独立演化出相似大体型，为岛屿巨型化机制提供了关键拼图，未来研究或将结合基因组学与生态环境，进一步揭示岛屿动物趋向巨型或矮化的根本驱动力。",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">Britain</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | Tubby troglodytidae</span></p>\n<h1>Some Scottish wrens are a striking case of “island syndrome”</h1>\n<h3>They have got much bigger than their mainland cousins</h3>\n<h3>July 9th 2026</h3>\n<p>Animals living on islands can develop strange characteristics. (Just look at the British.) Isolated, safe from mainland predators and facing less competition for resources, island-dwellers often evolve differently from mainland relatives. Some develop “island syndromes”. For example, small animals get bigger and big animals get smaller. The dodo of Mauritius evolved from the size of a pigeon to that of a large turkey, losing the use of its wings along the way.</p>\n<p>Some wrens in Scotland have developed the syndrome. Cut off from mainland Britain for thousands of years, two subspecies on St Kilda and Shetland, a pair of archipelagoes, have evolved to be much larger than mainland wrens, says a recent paper in the Evolutionary Journal of the Linnean Society.</p>\n<p>Researchers set mist nets beside speakers playing recordings of wren song across Shetland, Fair Isle, the Outer Hebrides and St Kilda—a method to lure birds out of cover. “Catching them was a nightmare,” says Michal Jezierski, the paper’s lead author. Wrens are so territorial that when song played, the birds simply sang back, refusing to budge. Still, the team caught 45 wrens, enough to study systematically. Using data of historical specimens from the National Museums Scotland, and body-mass records from the British Trust for Ornithology, they compared the island wrens with their mainland relatives—and with 695 other island-mainland bird pairs.</p>\n<p>Fair Isle wrens were a similar size to mainland ones, and those on the Outer Hebrides were a tad larger. But St Kilda and Shetland wrens were gigantic: the largest was twice as heavy as the smallest mainland wren. They are in the top 25% most extreme cases of “island gigantism” recorded, much like New Zealand’s kakapo, the world’s heaviest parrot. They also had distinctive songs. </p>\n<p>Only a small share of the genes that govern size overlapped in the two bird populations, despite them being similarly large. This suggests they evolved in parallel, via different genetic paths. It is still unclear why island animals become giants (or dwarfs). But Scottish wrens provide a piece of the puzzle. <span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>For more expert analysis of the biggest stories in Britain, <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/newsletters/blighty\">sign up</a> to Blighty, our weekly subscriber-only newsletter.</p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//britain/2026/07/09/some-scottish-wrens-are-a-striking-case-of-island-syndrome\">https://www.economist.com//britain/2026/07/09/some-scottish-wrens-are-a-striking-case-of-island-syndrome</a> </p>"
